metaData.descriptionCS: The child scans a search group and indicates whether the target symbol(s) matches any of the symbols in the search group within a specified time limit.

questions.title: A: Sample Items
questions.correctInstructionsHTML:
Correct response:

Say, That’s right. Now you know how to do them.
questions.incorrectInstructionsHTML:
Incorrect response(s):

Correct the error(s) immediately, as follows:

If the child incorrectly marks NO on the first or third sample item, say, That’s not quite right. This shape (point to first target symbol) is the same as this one (point to matching symbol in search group), so you should mark it.

If the child incorrectly marks a non-target symbol in the search group on the first or third sample item, say, That’s not quite right. This shape (point to error) is not the same as this one (point to target symbol), so you should not mark it.

If the child incorrectly marks the rotated target symbol on the second sample item, say, That’s not quite right. Even though this shape (point to rotated target in search group) looks like this one (point to target symbol), you should not mark it because it’s turned the wrong way. You should mark the NO box.

If the child incorrectly marks any other symbol in the search group on the second sample item, say, That’s not quite right. This shape (point to error) is not the same as this one (point to target symbol), so you should not mark it.

Do not proceed with the test items until the child has correctly completed the sample items and understands the task. If it is clear that the child will not understand the task with further instruction, use the pencil icon to add a note saying the child did not understand the task. Enter 0 for the total correct and total incorrect scores for the subtest. Refer to the Invalidating Subtest Scores section in Chapter 2 of the WISC–V Administration and Scoring Manual for more information.

When the child has successfully completed the sample items, proceed to Test Items.
